div.p:
Answ. To this I answere; They that writ them (howsoeuer indued
with rare gifts, and worthie Instruments of Gods Glorie) were men, and so might erre in that, as well as points of greater consequence, matters of faith; and somuch the rather, because they receiued many of them by report from others. Againe, they that did them, were men, & so might erre, quoad finem & intentionem, in regard of the end and intention; for who knowes whether in euery particular miracle they did intend and ayme at a right and due end? Surely, me thinks, Seneca's morall rule vsed in another case, may here not vnfitly bee applyed,Sen. Ep. 3. ad Lucil. Vtrumque vitium est, & omnibus credere & nulli: to beleeue all and to beleeue none, is neither of them good; it is neither safe to beleeue all, nor pious to beleeue none: To beleeue all, many will thinke were too rash;
but to beleeue none, I am sure were too irreligious. Therefore, as the blessed Apostle speaketh of Doctrines, so say I of those Miracles,1. Thes. 5.21. Prooue all things, hold fast that which is good: proue them ex ratione facti, ex ratione miraculi, ex ratione finis; proue them (if it may be) whether they were truely done, whether truely miraculous, whether destined to a true end: and then, quod bonum est retinete: hold fast and approue that which is good.
